{"timestamp":"2026-05-19T11:48:39.838Z","taskId":"KB-003","text":" 4. The design properly mutes wavesurfer's audio output (`setVolume(0)`) so howler.js remains the sole audio source, uses the `interaction` event (not `seeking`) for user-initiated seek callbacks, and correctly converts wavesurfer's time-in-seconds event data back to a 0–1 fraction for the audio engine. The test file provides thorough coverage of all public functions","type":"text","agent":"reviewer"}
{"timestamp":"2026-05-19T11:48:41.435Z","taskId":"KB-003","text":" including edge cases.\n\n### Issues Found\n\n1. **`waveformRenderer.ts` — [minor] `loadAudio` doesn't handle the `load()` Promise rejection.** `ws.load(url)` returns a `Promise<void>` in wavesurfer.js v7. If the audio fetch or decode fails, the rejection is silently swallowed. While the PROMPT doesn't call for error handling here specifically, consider adding a `.","type":"text","agent":"reviewer"}
{"timestamp":"2026-05-19T11:48:43.155Z","taskId":"KB-003","text":"catch()` that logs a warning or fires a status callback, since a failed waveform load would leave the waveform area blank with no indication to the user.\n\n2. **`waveformRenderer.test.ts` — [minor] Overly complex mock setup.** The test file defines a top-level `vi.mock('wavesurfer.js', ...)`, then in `beforeEach` uses `vi.resetModules()` + `vi.doMock","type":"text","agent":"reviewer"}
{"timestamp":"2026-05-19T11:48:45.602Z","taskId":"KB-003","text":"(...)` + re-imports `wavesurfer.js` to mutate `mod.default.create`, and then imports `waveformRenderer`. This dual-mocking approach is fragile. The top-level `vi.mock` alone (with `vi.clearAllMocks()` in `beforeEach`) would suffice since the mock factory returns a fresh `vi.fn()` each time. This doesn't affect correctness — the tests pass — but it makes the","type":"text","agent":"reviewer"}
{"timestamp":"2026-05-19T11:48:48.379Z","taskId":"KB-003","text":" setup harder to follow and maintain.\n\n### Pattern Violations\n\n- None. The module-level singleton pattern with `let ws: WaveSurfer | null = null` matches the same pattern used in `audioEngine.ts`. JSDoc comments are present on all exported functions, consistent with the documentation requirements.\n\n### Test Gaps\n\n- **Missing: test that `init` passes custom options that override individual defaults.** The existing","type":"text","agent":"reviewer"}
{"timestamp":"2026-05-19T11:48:49.569Z","taskId":"KB-003","text":" \"merges custom options\" test checks `height: 96, waveColor: '#ff0000'` and asserts `barWidth: 2` is preserved, which is good. However, there's no test verifying that passing an empty `options` object still produces all defaults — currently covered implicitly by the \"correct default options\" test.\n- **Missing: test for `getWaveSurfer()` helper.**","type":"text","agent":"reviewer"}
{"timestamp":"2026-05-19T11:48:51.422Z","taskId":"KB-003","text":" The `getWaveSurfer` function is exported (marked `@internal`) but has no test. Minor since it's a test-only accessor.\n\n### Suggestions\n\n- **Consider `setTime(seconds)` instead of `seekTo(fraction)` for the sync loop.** `seekTo(progress)` seeks wavesurfer's internal media element. While volume is 0, the media element still buffers from the seeked position.","type":"text","agent":"reviewer"}
{"timestamp":"2026-05-19T11:48:53.821Z","taskId":"KB-003","text":" An alternative would be `ws.setTime(currentTime)` (available in v7) which also updates the visual without the semantic implication of a \"seek.\" This is a minor optimization for a future iteration — the current approach works correctly as designed.\n- **The `progressColor` comment is excellent.** The inline note explaining why `var(--color-accent)` can't be used (canvas `fillStyle` doesn't resolve CSS","type":"text","agent":"reviewer"}
